    "engine": "knitr",
    "markdown": "---\ntitle: \"Beyond pairwise correlation: capturing nonlinear and higher-order dependence with distance statistics\"\nauthors:\n  - name: Benjamin Avanzi\n    affiliation: Centre for Actuarial Studies, Department of Economics, University of Melbourne, Australia\n  - name: Guillaume Boglioni Beaulieu\n    affiliation: School of Risk and Actuarial Studies, University of New South Wales, Sydney, NSW 2052, Australia\n  - name: Pierre Lafaye de Micheaux\n    affiliation: School of Mathematics and Statistics, University of New South Wales, Sydney, NSW 2052, Australia\n  - name: Ho Ming Lee\n    affiliation: \n      - Centre for Actuarial Studies, Department of Economics, University of Melbourne, Australia\n      - Faculty of Economics and Business, KU Leuven, Belgium\n    corresponding: true\n  - name: Bernard Wong\n    affiliation: School of Risk and Actuarial Studies, University of New South Wales, Sydney, NSW 2052, Australia\n  - name: Rui Zhou\n    affiliation: Centre for Actuarial Studies, Department of Economics, University of Melbourne, Australia\n  \nabstract: |\n  Measuring and modelling dependence between risks is crucial in many actuarial applications, such as when assessing diversification benefits or setting capital requirements. Current industry practice relies heavily on Pearson's correlation coefficient, despite well-known limitations. In particular, it captures only linear association, is restricted to pairwise relationships, and does not naturally extend to multivariate settings involving multiple random variables or random vectors. Sole reliance on Pearson's linear correlation may fail to detect important nonlinear, higher-order, and mutual dependence structures. \n  \n  In this paper, we introduce several distance-based dependence statistics which do not suffer from the same limitations as correlation, and discuss how they can be used in actuarial applications. In the bivariate setting, we consider the Hellinger correlation [@geenens2022hellinger] as a tool for measuring dependence between two continuous univariate random variables, and distance covariance [@szekely2007measuring] as a tool for detecting and detecting dependence, especially when random vectors are involved. We then discuss extensions to higher-dimensional settings, including joint distance covariance for assessing mutual dependence across multiple random variables (or vectors), and the auto-distance correlation function for time series applications such as forcasting mortality rates over time.\n  \n  Throughout the paper, we illustrate the use of these tools in actuarial contexts and we direct the reader to available software implementations. Overall, the paper aims to provide actuaries with a practical introduction to distance-based dependence statistics and to show how they can complement classical correlation-based tools in actuarial workflows.\nbibliography: references.bib\nformat: html\nengine: knitr\n---\n\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n\n```{.r .cell-code .hidden}\nlibrary(ggplot2)\n```\n:::\n\n\n# Introduction\nThis is the code for the paper \n\n::: {.cell}\n\n```{.r .cell-code .hidden}\n# install.packages(\"ggplot2\")\n# install.packages(\"HellCor\")\nlibrary(HellCor)\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr .hidden}\n\n```\nLoading required package: energy\n```\n\n\n:::\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr .hidden}\n\n```\nLoading required package: FNN\n```\n\n\n:::\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr .hidden}\n\n```\nLoading required package: orthopolynom\n```\n\n\n:::\n\n```{.r .cell-code .hidden}\nlibrary(ggplot2)\nlibrary(patchwork)\n\ndata(\"worlddemographics\")\n\nworlddemographics_rank <- worlddemographics |>\n  transform(\n    FDeath = rank(Death.Rate.Pop) / (nrow(worlddemographics) + 1),\n    FBirth = rank(Birth.Rate.Pop) / (nrow(worlddemographics) + 1)\n  )\n\np1 <- ggplot(worlddemographics, aes(x = Death.Rate.Pop, y = Birth.Rate.Pop)) +\n  geom_point() +\n  geom_smooth(method = \"lm\", se = FALSE) +\n  labs(\n    x = \"Death rate per 1000 individuals\",\n    y = \"Birth rate per 1000 individuals\"\n  ) +\n  theme_minimal()\n\np2 <- ggplot(worlddemographics_rank, aes(x = FDeath, y = FBirth)) +\n  geom_point() +\n  geom_smooth(method = \"lm\", se = FALSE) +\n  labs(\n    x = \"Rank of death rate per 1000 individuals\",\n    y = \"Rank of birth rate per 1000 individuals\"\n  ) +\n  theme_minimal()\n\np1 + p2\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr .hidden}\n\n```\n`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'\n```\n\n\n:::\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr .hidden}\n\n```\n`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'\n```\n\n\n:::\n\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n![](index_files/figure-pdf/birth_vs_death_rate_hellcor-1.pdf){fig-pos='H'}\n:::\n\n```{.r .cell-code .hidden}\n# ggsave(\n#   filename = \"saved_fig/birthvdeath.png\",\n#   plot = p1 + p2,\n#   width = 10,\n#   height = 4\n# )\n```\n:::\n\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n\n```{.r .cell-code .hidden}\nlibrary(dcov)\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr .hidden}\n\n```\n\nAttaching package: 'dcov'\n```\n\n\n:::\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr .hidden}\n\n```\nThe following objects are masked from 'package:energy':\n\n    dcor, dcor.test, dcor2d, dcov, dcov2d, pdcor, pdcor.test, pdcov\n```\n\n\n:::\n\n```{.r .cell-code .hidden}\nset.seed(123)\nHellCor::HellCor(worlddemographics$Birth.Rate.Pop, worlddemographics$Death.Rate.Pop, pval.comp = TRUE)\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}\n\n```\n$Hcor\n[1] 0.6903191\n\n$p.value\n[1] 0\n\n$conf.int\n[1] NA\n\n$Khat\n[1] 3\n\n$Lhat\n[1] 3\n```\n\n\n:::\n\n```{.r .cell-code .hidden}\nset.seed(123)\ndcov::dcor.test(worlddemographics$Birth.Rate.Pop, worlddemographics$Death.Rate.Pop)\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}\n\n```\n$statistic\n[1] 0.1255081\n\n$replicates\n           [,1]       [,2]       [,3]        [,4]       [,5]        [,6]\n[1,] 0.01353002 0.02002241 0.00932196 0.008858113 0.00848732 0.007983672\n            [,7]       [,8]        [,9]    